        "This approach is problematic only if the procurement manager approves the invoices; if rejected, no ethical violation has occurred"
      ],
      "correct_answer": 1,
      "explanation": "This covert operation crosses ethical and legal boundaries. Even in fraud investigations, CFEs must not create or participate in fraudulent activities themselves. This approach involves the CFE fabricating false documents and actively inducing someone to commit a crime, which could constitute entrapment, conspiracy to commit fraud, or other illegal conduct. It violates professional standards that require fraud examiners to conduct investigations lawfully and ethically. Appropriate covert techniques might include undercover observation, confidential interviews, or testing controls through legitimate means, but never by actually committing fraud. The CFE's intent not to collect payment does not negate the fact that false documents were created and submitted. Authorization from counsel does not make illegal activity legal. Whether or not the target approves the invoices, the CFE has already engaged in creating and submitting false documents, which is itself problematic.",
      "topic": "Covert Operations",
      "subtopic": "Ethical Boundaries in Undercover Investigations",
